  <tr>
  	<td class="sub_LateNewsHeader">Tuvalu Minister dies in Suva</td>
  </tr>
  

<tr>
<td>
<br>
<div class="sub_BodyTextBlue">
<img class="news_exclusive" src="/web/20130105045448im_/http://www.islandsbusiness.com/images/ib_news_exclusive.gif" alt="Islands Business Exclusive"><strong>Islands Business Exclusive</strong>
</div>
</td>
</tr>


<tr>
  	<td>
<table width="100%" border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0">
  <tr>
    <td align="left"><div class="sub_BodyPad"><font class="sub_BodyTextBlue"><br><b></b></font></div>
    															</td>
    <td valign="middle" align="right"><img src="/web/20130105045448im_/http://www.islandsbusiness.com/images/flags/tuvalu.gif"></td>
  </tr>
</table>
	</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
  <td valign="top" width="100%">
<div class="sub_BodyPad"><font class="sub_BodyTextBlueItalised"><br>Robert Matau</font></div>
<div class="sub_BodyPad"><font class="sub_BodyTextBlue">Mon, 24 Dec 2012 </font></div>
<div class="sub_BodyPad"><font class="sub_BodyTextBlue"><p>
	&nbsp;</p>
<p>
	<strong>SUVA, Fiji</strong> ---- (<em>www.islandsbusiness.com</em>)TUVALU&rsquo;S Finance Minister Lotoala Metia passed away last week at the Suva Private Hospital, Tuvalu Government officials confirmed.</p>
<p>
	His permanent secretary Minute Alapati Taupo confirmed he died on Friday December 21, but referred all further details to the Tuvalu High Commission in Suva.</p>
<p>
	Metia was battling with illness for the last four months in New Zealand and was only recently flown back to Tuvalu to attend the December sitting of parliament to approve the nation&rsquo;s budget.</p>
<p>
	He flew to Tuvalu from New Zealand on December 13 voted for the budget on December 17 but was admitted at the Intensive Care Unit in Tuvalu for the duration of his stay, a parliamentarian confirmed.</p>
<p>
	He flew to Fiji on December 20 and was admitted to the Suva Private Hospital where he died on Friday evening December 21.</p>
<p>
	Metia was first elected to Parliament in 2006 winning his Nukufetau seat and was appointed Minister of Finance, Economic Planning and Industries in the then Prime Minister Apisai Ielemia's Cabinet.</p>
<p>
	While he retained his seat in Parliament in the 2010 general election, he was not selected to Cabinet by the then Prime Minister Maatia Toafa.</p>
<p>
	Three months later, in December, he supported Willy Telavi 's successful attempt to oust the Toafa government in a motion of no confidence.</p>
<p>
	Telavi became Prime Minister, and appointed Metia to his Cabinet, as Minister for Finance.</p>
<p>
	However, a month later his constituents from Nukufetau demanded his resignation in a peaceful protest on the island.&nbsp; Members of the powerful council of elders or Falekaupule from his island wanted to meet him to persuade him to reconsider his allegiance to Telavi in a move that would have shifted power from Telavi to Metia&rsquo;s fellow Nukufetau MP Enele Sopoaga and the opposition group.</p>
<p>
	It is being speculated that a by-election could be held as early as January.</p>
<p>
	He becomes the second cabinet minister to die since Telavi&rsquo;s successful win in 2010.&nbsp; Isaia Italeli died in July last year and was succeeded by his wife Pelenike Isaia who beat Opposition favourite Leneuoti Matusi by 62 votes to hand back the ultimate majority of 8 seats to Telavi as opposed to the Opposition&rsquo;s 7.</p>
<p>
	It is speculated that Metia&rsquo;s wife, Penieli who hails from Nukulaelae could be asked to stand in the Nukufetau constituency in the by-election.</p></font></div>
  </td></tr></tbody></table>


